{"type":"assistant","message":{"model":"claude-sonnet-4-6","id":"msg_01X5RViDMrsgWdTFbY8PBS6m","type":"message","role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"Let me analyze each behavior carefully, applying the KEY-QUESTIONS framework.\n\n**Behavior 1**: A request whose signature does not match its body is rejected with a 401 response; the body is not forwarded.\n\n- MOCK-MISS: This is signature verification logic — comparing HMAC-SHA256 of body against header. This is a local function's logic.\n- REAL-INFRA: No OS, network, subprocess needed. The HMAC computation is pure crypto.\n- MOCK-HIDE: Could mock the crypto? But HMAC-SHA256 is deterministic — no need.\n- LLM-DEP: No AI/ML involved.\n\n\n- MULTI-STEP: No.\n\nThe failure mode is either a bug in the signature verification function itself or in how the handler wires the rejection response. I can test this at the unit level by checking the verify function directly, or at the integration level by testing that the handler properly rejects with 401 and doesn't forward the body. Since Node.js HTTP handlers typically use something like supertest to make real HTTP calls to an in-process server, this falls into integration testing without needing external infrastructure.\n\nThe signature verification algorithm (HMAC-SHA256 comparison) is unit-level, but the full behavior of rejecting with 401 and not forwarding the body requires the handler's wiring to be correct — that's integration. The minimum viable test is integration level, where the handler, verification, and queue wiring all work together without real external infrastructure.\n\n**Behavior 2**: An event gets written to the persistent queue before the HTTP 200 response goes back to the sender.\n\nThis is about ordering — the queue write must happen before the response. Testing this requires checking the interaction between the handler and queue, and I could use a fake or stub queue to verify the ordering. If I'm using a real persistent queue, that changes the testing approach.\n\nA stub queue can catch the ordering failure by recording when the write was called relative to when the response was sent. So integration testing is sufficient here too.\n\n**Behavior 3**: The handler returns the HTTP response without waiting for downstream processing to complete.\n\nThis is about async behavior — the handler doesn't block on downstream work. I could test this with a fake slow downstream processor to verify the response comes back before processing finishes.\n\n**Behavior 4**: The response arrives within 3 seconds wall-clock time even when downstream processing of earlier events is slow and concurrent.\n\nThis is a timing and performance requirement under concurrent load with slow downstream processing — a different beast entirely.\n\nI could test this with in-process slow stubs and concurrent requests using supertest, which would make it Integration level. The key insight is that I don't need real external infrastructure to verify non-blocking behavior; I just need a slow mock downstream that takes longer than 3 seconds, then fire concurrent requests and confirm they return quickly. But I'm wondering if the real failure mode here — where concurrent requests expose race conditions under actual OS scheduling — might only surface with real infrastructure. the queue write itself. For deduplication to work across restarts, the state needs to persist somewhere — likely a database or cache layer rather than just in-memory. So this is really an Integration test: I need to verify the handler checks the dedup store and skips the queue write when it finds a duplicate ID.\n\nFor Behavior 6, I'm testing how the handler responds when the queue is at capacity. I'll stub the queue to report a \"full\" error and verify the handler returns a 503 with the appropriate Retry-After header — no real infrastructure needed here, just mocking the queue's response.\n\nBehavior 7 is different: I'm testing the queue's own capacity enforcement, not the handler's response to it. If the queue is an external service like Redis or RabbitMQ, this requires System-level testing with the actual infrastructure. If it's a local implementation, I might get away with Unit or Integration, but the \"persistent\" nature suggests I'll need to test against real storage to verify capacity limits are actually enforced. Integration.\n\nGiven the context says \"persistent queue\" — this likely uses a real storage backend. Testing capacity enforcement requires hitting the actual queue implementation with real data. This is at least Integration (if using a local in-process queue implementation) or System (if using a real external queue service).\n\nThe problem is: the behavior says \"the persistent queue actually enforces its configured capacity limit\" — the word \"actually\" suggests we need to test the real queue, not a stub. You can't mock the queue here since we're testing the queue itself.\n\nIf the persistent queue is a local file-based queue, Integration. If it's an external service (Redis), System.\n\nGiven the language \"persistent queue\" without specification, I'll say Integration is the minimum if the queue is implemented locally, but System is more likely because \"persistent\" usually implies an external service or at minimum filesystem operations.\n\nThe question really comes down to what \"persistent\" means here — whether it's a custom Node.js implementation with filesystem backing, an external service like Redis or RabbitMQ, or a database-backed queue. Since capacity enforcement might only work correctly with the real implementation and persistent queues typically involve OS-level persistence or network calls, I'm leaning toward System as the classification. the real module (hitting real filesystem) would catch it. That's Integration if using real local filesystem (no subprocess, no network).\n\nHmm, I'll go with Integration as minimum but note System is likely needed for external queue services. The level_probabilities should reflect this uncertainty.\n\nActually, re-reading: REAL-INFRA says \"could an in-process fake (mock HTTP client, fake filesystem, stub subprocess) reproduce the exact failure?\" For behavior 7, we ARE testing the queue itself — we cannot fake it. So we need the real queue. If it uses real filesystem, that's still Integration in some interpretations (local I/O). If it uses network, System.\n\nI'll go with Integration as minimum level but with high System probability too.\n\nLet me now compile my final answers. B1 tests handler wiring and signature verification with an in-process server via supertest, so that's Integration. B2 checks queue write ordering before the HTTP response, which a stub queue with order-tracking can verify. B3 validates the async pattern where the handler doesn't await downstream work, caught by a slow in-process mock. B4 measures response timing under concurrent slow downstream calls—in-process supertest handles this without needing real concurrent HTTP pressure. B5 covers deduplication across the handler and store with a stub, which works in-process. B6 is cut off but likely follows the same pattern. For behavior 1, I need to check whether Unit testing is actually sufficient. The behavior requires validating that a 401 response is returned with no body forwarding, which means testing the full handler integration rather than just the signature algorithm in isolation. The MOCK-MISS principle applies here — the failure could stem from either the signature validation logic or the handler's response wiring, so I need multiple modules interacting to properly test this.\n\nBehaviors 3 and 4 are related but distinct: behavior 3 tests the non-blocking pattern itself (catchable with a slow mock), while behavior 4 validates the timing guarantee under concurrent load, making both Integration-level tests.\n\nNow I'm assigning probability distributions across test levels for each behavior. For behavior 1, signature rejection leans heavily toward Integration since the handler wiring is essential. Behavior 2, queue write before 200, also skews Integration-heavy given the sequencing requirement.\n\nBehavior 3 follows similarly at 75% Integration. For behavior 4, the wall-clock timing under real concurrent load makes me reconsider—while supertest handles concurrency, actual timing guarantees might require System-level infrastructure, so I'm bumping that to 45%.\n\nBehaviors 5 and 6 continue the pattern, with deduplication and retry logic both requiring Integration-level testing to verify the full flow.\n\nBehavior 7 is different—queue capacity enforcement is fundamentally about System behavior, so that gets the highest weight at 60%, with Integration at 30% for testing the enforcement mechanism itself.\n\nNow I'm verifying all the probability distributions sum to 1.0 across each behavior.\n\nLooking at the test descriptions, I need to make sure the plan_consistent values actually match what each test would require—for instance, B1's integration test would use an HTTP client to send a request with an invalid signature and check the response.\n\nThe signature verification test definitely needs the handler, signature verifier, and queue stub all working together, so Integration is the right call. B2 requires the same setup with queue timing verification. B3 needs the handler wired to an async queue with a slow downstream stub to confirm the response comes back before processing finishes. B4 is trickier since it involves concurrent requests with real timing—Integration works if I use in-process mocks, though a System test with actual concurrent HTTP would be more realistic. B5 requires the handler and dedup state to verify duplicate event IDs only write once to the queue.\n\nFor B6, I'd stub the queue to return a full error and check that the handler responds with 503 and the Retry-After header. B7 goes further by using a real persistent queue like Redis configured with capacity limits, filling it to capacity, and verifying the rejection behavior. All of these maintain plan_consistent = true at their respective levels.","signature":""}],"stop_reason":null,"stop_sequence":null,"usage":{"input_tokens":3,"cache_creation_input_tokens":12919,"cache_read_input_tokens":0,"cache_creation":{"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":0,"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens":12919},"output_tokens":8,"service_tier":"standard","inference_geo":"not_available"},"context_management":null},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"10f2fffa-a9a2-4455-b933-7f0b129686f0","uuid":"9a086e5b-6d66-455b-b53a-149f0fd5c173"}
